            <img alt="This black-and-white photo shows a crowd of people in the early 1920s protesting the conviction of Sacco and Vanzetti, Italian immigrants accused of robbery and murder." data-uuid="2b75b73973674ed293edfb37fb8b6f9c" src="../../img/module_25_lesson02/ms_snlese454149_946p.jpg" />
            <div class="figcaption" data-uuid="79390fee71e94f39b637938db61d654b">
                <h5 data-uuid="5255336c64a241ecb75848fd8c6334db">Sacco and Vanzetti</h5>
                <p class="caption" data-uuid="2fd2cc6d633342eaa2651530c1df8442">Supporters of Sacco and Vanzetti held rallies and raised money for the immigrants’ defense. The men were found guilty and were executed in 1927.</p>
            </div>
        </figure>
        <h3 data-uuid="d2ea27ee61ab49b4b30fbf444a020e12">Restricting Immigration</h3>
        <p data-uuid="26e3a500c23b4fb6904c675bed36b477">Some people thought that a general fear of foreigners from different ethnic groups influenced the Sacco and Vanzetti case. Many recent immigrants were poor and did not speak English. Some Americans saw them as a threat to their jobs and culture. Immigrants “fill places that belong to the loyal wage-earning citizens of America,” said Alabama senator James Thomas Heflin.<br />
        </p>
